postcontent: Seller Stock #: XB90015hs Many if not most gun owning households have a Mossberg 500 on the premises. Photos show a specimen of Mossberg’s 18 inch barrel for standard model 500s, and we have outfitted it with a Trench type heat shield. This apparatus will give a wood stocked 12 gauge model 500 an appearance similar to the classic Winchester model 12s issued to many of our soldiers in Conflicts from World War Two through Vietnam. It will also turn a model 500 field gun into a compact and formidable home protection device. Barrel Manufacturer is O.F. Mossberg of Torreon, Mexico, the facility where most of the company’s barrels have been made for the past 20 years. Construction is U.S. steel, explicitly labeled on the barrel. Chambering is for 12 gauge shells, both for 2 3/4 inch and for 3 inch shells interchangeably. Finish is semi-gloss blue. Length is 18 5/8 inches of bore proper, measured from the muzzle to the breech face. Overall length is 19 11/16 inches from the muzzle to the end of the chamber hood. Heat shield is black polymer construction, manufactured in the world’s most populous nation. It attaches with four screws in front of the barrel lug, with an additional brace over the chamber area of the barrel, as the photos show. This barrel will fit any Mossberg model 500 shotgun chambered in 12 gauge whose magazine tube will hold 5 each 2 3/4 inch shells, and whose magazine tube measures 13 1/2 inches from the receiver face to the end of its magazine tube. That includes over 95 percent of Mossberg 500s in existence today. It also fits Western Auto Revelation 310 series 12 gauge pump shotguns; it also fits Wards Western Field models 505, 509, 524, 534, 536, 539, 550 all variants, because those were made by Mossberg for Western Auto and for Montgomery Wards beginning in the 1960s. It will not fit an 8 shot model 500 whose magazine tube is 19 inches long. It will not fit a 20 gauge Mossberg; will not fit a .410 gauge Mossberg; will not fit the dump lever of a 1947 John Deere Manure Spreader. It will only fit Mossberg 500 series pump or slide action shotguns whose magazine tubes hold five 2 3/4 inch 12 gauge shells. It will not render 1960s and 1970s production shotguns that were chambered only for 2 3/4 inch shells magnum capable. Military Armament Corporation
Semi-Automatic.  Caliber 9mm. / can be converted to 45ACP
MAC – 10 Threaded Barrel
Threaded barrel is standard Cobray and MAC type suppressor threads.  ¾ X 10 TPI.
Original Magazine
**Fake** can suppresor (As seen in picture)
Manual
Snap-on shoulder holster made by DeSantis. The holster alone cost $200. 

The MAC-10 (Military Armament Corporation Model 10, officially the M-10) is a compact blowback operated machine pistol developed by Gordon Ingram in 1964.   It is chambered in either 45 ACP or 9mm.   A two-stage suppressor by Sonic’s was designed for the MAC-10, which not only abated the noise created, but made it easier to control on full automatic.
Military Armament Corporation (MAC), based in Powder Springs Georgia from 1970-1976 was the first company to commercially produce the MAC Model 10 (MAC-10).This is the company started by Gordon Ingram that designed and built the first MAC.    MAC marketed a number of different weapons, but the MAC-10 (chambered in 9 mm and later in.45 ACP) and the high cyclic rate (approx. 1600 rpm) MAC-11 (chambered in .380) were its mainstays.   MAC declared bankruptcy in 1976 and went out of business. 
Military Armament Corporation in Stephenville, TX took the MAC design from the Powder Springs plant and redesigned the gun to be "better".  In short, they redesigned the trigger mechanism, the safety, and the stock for better fit and  reliability.

title: For Sale:  Emerson folders and cold steel folder
postcontent:
I have three folding knives for sale.  I have too many folders and I am paring down a bit.  I do not have boxes for any of these knives.  
All of the knives were professionally sharpened by Precision Sharpening near Lincoln and Seneca.  They are sharper than they were from the factory and I take all of my knives to them to put the best edge on.  Each knife has an individual price. 

1) Cold Steel Ti-Lite (Zy-Ex) 4".  This is the "lesser" expensive version which has a zytel handle instead of a metal handle.  It is super light weight, has a slick double ground long blade.  It has a false edge on the back side (only one side of the knife is sharp).  It was great for pocket carry and didn't get in the way.  I prefer serrations in a blade and didn't end up carrying this around as much. 
[B]$40 obo[/B]

2) Emerson/Benchmade CQC7 Spec War Model Tanto blade (stone washed).  This was my EDC knife for a while.  It proved extremely reliable, tough, sharp, and has been a good knife.  The tanto edge had a minor knick, which I had Precision Sharpening re-work.  Aesthetically, the transition from the 1st edge to the 2nd edge had to be moved but this does not affect function.  If you like having a nice knife and want to have one that you can use and not cringe when you have to cut something, this is your knife.  It was an early model with the bead blast finish.  The blade is clean and smooth, despite the minor discoloration[B]$80[/B]

3) Emerson Mini-Commander 2002 Drop point, partially serrated blade.  This was a backup knife I carried.  I wore it to work but it was never/rarely used.  I carried multiple knives and this was strictly a SHTF knife.  It has a beautiful mirror polish on the edge as a result of the buffing/sharpening.  It also has the wave/crest pocket opening feature.  Just like the other Emerson, the blade is nice and thick.  [B]$135[/B]

These knives were meant to be carried, so I'd rather give them the chance to do their thing versus sit in my drawer.  The only trade I am interested in is an OTF, preferably Microtech Ultratech.

Email is the best way to reach me.  nobletitus at gmail dot com.
